   <abstract >Contemporary racism poses a serious barrier to addressing the pervasive issue of racial inequality. Thus, it is important to identify the characteristic features of such racism and who are the kind of people more likely to perpetuate it. With this aim, the current work aimed to unmask some of the underlying features of contemporary racism and show how people's internal (IMS) and external (EMS) motivation to be nonprejudiced (Plant &amp; Devine, 1998) plays a crucial role in determining who engages in such racism. Across four studies, we show that IMS is associated with other-focused justice sensitivity (Study 1), other-focused and affiliative language (Study 2), unambiguous acknowledgment of racial issues (Studies 2-4), support for systemic measures to combat inequality (Studies 2-3), and more information seeking of information related to racial-issues (Study 4). In contrast, EMS is associated with greater self-focused justice sensitivity (Study 1), psychologically distant and ambiguous language (Study 2), distancing from racial topics (Studies 2-4), overestimation of racial equality (Study 1 and 4), and less information seeking of race-related information (Study 4). Overall, the current work demonstrates that one of the keys to addressing the issue of racial inequality and contemporary racism is to find ways to foster internal motivation to respond without prejudice.</abstract>
